ry><gtr:grantReference>ES/I031715/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This study of the descendants of survivors of the 1822 massacres of the Aegean island of Chios offers a setting in which to research the ways in which extreme political violence affects the social fabric of a community over a period of six generations, or two hundred years. In the spring of 1822, during the Greek war of independence, the Ottoman navy perpetrated a series of massacres on the island that annihilated nine tenths of the population, leaving 10,000 survivors in a population of 120,000. There are now two communities amongst which collective memories of the massacres can be studied: the diaspora, and those who remained on the island. This project compares the role of collective memories of the massacres among these two groups.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>It investigates why events that took place nearly two centuries ago remain significant today. Specifically, it will examine the ways in which collective memories may incorporate more recent social and political events, including the upheaval of the exchange of populations in 1922, the German occupation of WWII, and the civil war that followed. It will also embrace current anxieties regarding Greco-Turkish relations and the financial crisis that is affecting the people of Chios so dramatically now.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2013-09-28</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2011-09-29</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>187555</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Conference panel</gtr:description><gtr:form>A formal working group, expert panel or dialogue</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>International</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>27283D6A-B641-47F3-9CEE-6E392D1A5CC1</gtr:id><gtr:impact>I co-organised a panel for the 2014 Association of Social Anthropologists of the UK and Commonwealth (ASA) conference in Edinburgh. The panel, 'Humanity at sea: hybridity and seafaring', examined ships as hybrid places, addressing the human need and potential to create and adjust to such composite environments. 
In addition to chairing the session I presented a paper entitled 'The love of flowers: boats, time and the navigation of catastrophe in the Aegean'. The research for the paper was conducted during my ESRC research period.

I have put together a proposal for an edited collection resulting from the panel.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>5448ef08c29e65.37321386</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Public/other audiences</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://www.nomadit.co.uk/asa/asa2014/panels.php5?View=Panels</gtr:url><gtr:year>2014</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Research seminar presentation, Hellenic Observatory, London School of Economics</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>International</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>88385FC9-B641-4590-9F48-6953446321C7</gtr:id><gtr:impact>A research paper on the sovereign debt crisis in Greece was presented to the staff of the Hellenic observatory and to the press.

